{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"968bd4cc-69b5-4326-be5a-d19f1b6dbd08","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the MAUI layout engine to skip safe-area padding, but on **Android** the window itself still doesn't draw behind the system bars unless you explicitly enable edge-to-edge mode at the platform level.\n\n**What you're missing (Android):**\n\nIn `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    // Allow content to render behind system bars\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n    Window!.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window!.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n**On iOS**, also set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the image itself:\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       ios:Image.IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n```\n\n(with `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"`)\n\n**Summary:** `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` handles the MAUI layout layer, but Android needs `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` to actually extend the window behind system bars, and iOS views need `IgnoreSafeArea` to break out of the safe area at the platform level.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cfd0b27b-66b1-42cb-aa2e-3c3a34d044d2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` isn't sufficient by itself. The key thing they're likely missing is that they also need to opt into edge-to-edge rendering at the platform level.\n\nIn .NET MAUI (especially with newer versions targeting .NET 8+), there are a few things to consider:\n\n\n- On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should allow content to extend behind the status bar and home indicator, but the behavior depends on how the page is configured.\n- On Android, edge-to-edge rendering is the default starting with Android 15, though earlier versions may require explicit configuration to draw behind system bars.\n- For .NET MAUI specifically, I need to consider platform-specific settings like `Window.DecorFitsSystemWindows` on Android and potentially `UIViewControllerBasedStatusBarAppear` on iOS to get the full edge-to-edge effect.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the user wants the app to draw behind the system bars themselves, not just handle safe areas. On Android, that means configuring the activity to draw edge-to-edge and making the status and navigation bars transparent, while on iOS it involves adjusting how the view controller handles extended layout edges. to add safe area padding, but the system still doesn't let the app draw behind the bars unless edge-to-edge mode is enabled at the platform level. The real fix on Android involves setting `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` in `MainActivity.cs` to enable edge-to-edge rendering, and then making the system bars transparent so content can actually extend behind them.\n\nOn iOS, I need to be more careful about which property actually works—`SafeAreaEdges` might not be available depending on the .NET MAUI version, and the approach for ignoring safe area has changed across releases.\n\nThe real issue is that on Android, just setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` doesn't actually make the window extend behind the system bars—that requires explicit window configuration at the platform level. I should focus on giving the user the concrete fix for that.","outputTokens":1799,"requestId":"5026:63E52:1D2F437:20543A2:69FA92AA"},"id":"7d5a239e-ef06-454d-891b-8cb4038baa1c","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:01:01.947Z","parentId":"3c7d6d48-7b42-40b4-8832-b